A:

Here is an idea for a solution:

Array.reduce(function (result, item) {
  if (item.type === 'tree') {
    result.push(item);
    return result;
  } else {
    return result;
  }
}, []).filter(function (item) {
  return item.type === 'animal'
});

This solution is approximately 2x as fast.
This algorithm requires the use of a temporary result array.
If you are worried about performance, you can use a stack to hold the temporary values instead.

A:

The problem is, a single tree will have a lot of "animal" objects.
You can do it in a single pass:
var classes = {
  type: "tree",
  objects: []
};

for (var i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
  var item = {
    type: "animal",
    objects: []
  };

  // push a new "animal" object on the array
  classes.objects.push(item);

  // define the type of the object
  item.type = "animal";

  // check if the object is a tree
  if (item.type === "tree") {
    // create a new object from the tree
    item.objects = item.objects.concat(classes.objects);
  }
}

var result = [];

for (var i = 0; i < classes.objects.length; i++) {
  result.push(classes.objects[i]);
}

return result;

Update:
If you want to sort the result by type, you can use a Map instead of an array. The Map acts like an array but there are no indices. It is not ordered, so you have to do a linear search to find the object you are looking for.
